'''Spurius Nautius Rutilus''' ([[Latin]], ''Spurius Nautius Rutilus '') was a Roman [[Roman Republic|Republican]] [[politician]], possibly of the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|Patrician]] gens [[Nautii]] during the beginning of the 5th century BC. He served as [[Consul of Rome]] in 488 BC, serving together with [[Sextus Furius Medullinus (consul 488 BC)|Sextus Furius Medullinus Fusus]].

== Family Origins ==

The [[Nautii]] [[gens]] was a Roman [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|Patrician]] family in the old Republican period. Spurius was the father of [[Gaius Nautius Rutilus]] who followed in his father's footsteps serving as consul in 475 and in 458 BC.

== Biography ==

Spurius Nautius Rutilus was elected consul in 488 BC, serving together with [[Sextus Furius Medullinus Fusus]]. [[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]] first mentions Spurius Nautius in 493 BC as having been one of the most distinguished young Patricians during the period of the succession of the plebs. He was consul in 488 which was also the same year that the [[Volscan]]s, under the command of [[Gaius Marcius Coriolanus|Coriolanus]] marched on [[Rome]] and besieged the city.

